"The sea is ours": Bolivia hopes court will open waterway to Pacific
Sailors patrol naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings flag with sea blue flags.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are covered with the motto: "The sea is ours. We are right
and duty to return to it.”
In landlocked Bolivia, the people can still remember a coastline the country lost to Chile, in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century. They long to sail in the Pacific again.
These hopes are perhaps stronger than in many decades while Bolivia awaits the verdict of the International Court of Justice to come on October 1, after five years of jurisdiction.
"Bolivia has drive, serenity and is united, and of course expects a positive result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians are going to look at the verdict of the International Court of Justice, hoping that the Court of The Hague supports Bolivia's claim, and that Chile - after decades of negotiations - gives Bolivia an independent exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic native president of Bolivia - who is striving to be elected again next year - has good reason to hope for a positive result.
"Now we will soon be returning to the Pacific," he promised in late August.
However, some analysts do not believe the court will allow Bolivia access to the sea - and that little would have changed itself if they had access.
The Netherlands-based United Nations Court of Justice has no power to transfer Chilean territory to Bolivia and has stipulated that they will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
That the court's verdict comes only six months after the last proceedings, indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
The last four years have far from promoted Bolivia's cause, they have done the opposite.
"The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
Morales, with his belligerent rhetoric, has killed what was left of Chile's goodwill, Zárate thought.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue negotiations, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the issue afterwards.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
The former president, Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who is Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to open new relations with Chile" and a chance to "set a line at 139 years of disagreement and rather benefit both," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used this maritime issue to win votes.
"Bolivia will never give up the right of access to the Pacific," he added.
"The verdict is a possibility to see what we need to do to forget the past."
