John Edward: Global citizens need language skills
Private schools in Scotland are known to be at a high academic level, and this continues in 2018 with excellent exam results, which are only enhanced by individual and joint success in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
With over 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), work to offer the best services to the students and their parents.
Self-employed schools aim to prepare their students for advanced and higher education, career paths and the role of global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are popular electives in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the message goes to his heart."
This is an important reminder that we can't just lean on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
By looking at the exam results from this year, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest standing grades for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who took foreign languages received A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 member schools, shows that 72 percent of students received A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who took German, 69 percent of those who took French, and 63 percent of those who took Spanish also received A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital qualities, which children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Languages such as electives are seen as equivalent to the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering studies, and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Properties Selection in 2014 showed that 17 percent of employers struggled to fill positions due to a lack of language skills in applicants.
Therefore, language in school is more and more important in order to prepare the youth for work.
With multiple job opportunities for linguists, these properties are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what kind of career a youth chooses, if they have learned a second language, they have a decent advantage in the future with such a skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person advantages in a competitive world.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak any language other than English well enough to keep a conversation going, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15 percent.
This is why it is so important to invest in language education for our children.
Knowing more languages, especially the languages used in developing countries, can give children a better chance of finding good jobs in the future.
In Scotland, each school is different in terms of the language they teach.
Many schools focus on the classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are classified as important in the UK as we look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be an abundance of languages to choose from in independent schools, and teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated and want to create a learning environment that will prepare children and provide the skills they need to close, no matter what the future brings.
One cannot deny that in this global, business-oriented environment, languages are vital for the country's future, so this must be mirrored in the education sector.
Modern languages should be called "international communication properties."
Autonomous schools will continue to offer this choice, thus offering diversity and high competence for Scotland's young people.
I'm fine with the fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools
