North Korea says there is no talk of rusting down unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that if sanctions continue, distrust of the United States will increase and that the country would by no means give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Government's Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures" to improve conditions over the past year, for example, they have stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear test site and promise not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we're not getting anything equivalent back from the United States," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances, it is not possible that we unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri, a well-known North Korean, has voiced several complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to the abolition of nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his resignation proved significant in not rejecting unilateral nuclear degradation, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint resignation issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first summit ever angered between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for "decreasing nuclear power in the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has wanted a formal end to the 1950–53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted talks to ease tough international sanctions in North Korea.
"The United States insists on "decreasing nuclear power first" and increasing the pressure of sanctions to achieve its purpose by coercion, and they even contradicted the "declaration to end peace," Ri said.
"The belief that sanctions can crack us is a false hope among those who are not interested in us.
But the problem is that as the sanctions continue, our distrust will only increase."
Ri did not mention anything about the plans for a new summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. president highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader, Moon Jae-in, over the past five months and added: "If the party in this call for the decommissioning of nuclear weapons were South Korea, and not the United States, the decommissioning of the Korean peninsula would not have stopped as it has now done"
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was not possible to stop North Korean missiles against the U.S. mainland, after evil President Trump called Kim a rocket man on suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much work still had to be done and that sanctions had to remain in place until North Korea deploys its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timeframe for this, saying, "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, told the F.N.'s Security Council on Thursday that: "Sanctions to the Security Council must still be vigorously upheld and without fail until we get the complete, final, verified decommissioning of the nuclear weapons."
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to throttle funds for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and afterwards said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a new summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemns him for making "gangster-like claims."
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States took "similar measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was seeking were safeguards promised by Trump in Singapore, and steps towards normalizing his relationship with Washington.
Harvard students take courses in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has helped all students get more sleep, in an effort to fight the growing macho culture of studying in caffeine drinks all night. That is, you use caffeine to stay awake all night to study.
One academic found that students at top universities often carelessly when it comes to the most basic thing - how to take care of yourself.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I being told this now, in adulthood?'
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleeping - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, rolled out for the first time this year, explains to students what is important for how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after students got seriously worse sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, as well as the importance of evening routines.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
'We know that it won't change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know, the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes, Prof. Czeisler added.
The pride culture of 24 hours still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring you get enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's secret weapon against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even avoiding gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in smelting mode and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, having been a student with him last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before starting at the prestigious institution.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, and also for when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" coming from electronic monitors and LED lighting, which can reset the inner clock overall, leading to problems falling asleep.
