Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and WE RECAP ... the day when the one who was to become the physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and targeting radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
As a scientific pillar ever since, the Geiger counter also became a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with the seemingly unlikely lazy cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Mann: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "There is a Geiger counter, it can be used to find radioactive minerals, for example uranium.
When you put these earphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms caused by the radioactivity of the minerals."
Evans: "Yes, now it bubbles!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
