National Trust eavesdrop on secret life of bats
New research conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano pipistrelles and also brown long-eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also perform mobile screenings using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and what species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, natural science advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will uncover which areas of habitat, natural homes, are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the acquisition of meadows and how it is best to maintain forested areas for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across Britain have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects resting places and loss of habitat/residence.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, such as flying paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, and also attacks by pet cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to find faults and obstacles in their flight route.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, resting place inspections and sometimes save lives.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitats.
But there is a lot about bats that is still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He underlines the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance within property, as it is possible that indefinite destruction of a single settlement can kill up to 400 female bats and young, and perhaps eradicate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their resting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to come in and help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are moving."
