Indonesia is located in the seismic Circle of Fire in the Pacific Ocean and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major quakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Aceh Province in northern Sumatra on 26 December, triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of these in Aceh.
2005: A series of major earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Several hundred died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck southern Java, the most populated island in Indonesia, triggering a tsunami that crashed into the south coast killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake struck near the city of Padang, capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake hit one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of about 10 metres that destroyed dozens of villages and killed around 300 people.
2016: A small quake hit the Pidie Jaya area of Aceh causing destruction and panic when people were reminded of the 2004 quake and tsunami.
